HOW TO RUN CODE

% python write_html.py

This will generate a series of HTML pages from .json templates using python librarys for
jinga2 and flask. The file mission_template.html directs how each page gets laid out

Alternative formats for mission_template.html files are in the templates/ directory.

The resulting HTML files are written into static_output/


However, the HTML that would be staged into the HEASARC website uses links to content that
is not present on the local machine. To address this,

% python postprocess.py

This python code reads each HTML file and replaces server side includes with a local copy
of the included file (with URL corrections) and for all instances of HREF and SRC links to
URLs not here (such as links to images or external pages), it adds a fully resolved URL
to make it work correctly in a local file setting.

E.g. <img src="/Images/misc_missions/alexis.jpg"> is changed to <img src="https://heasarc.gsfc.nasa.gov/Images/misc_missions/alexis.jpg">


HOWEVER

there are four files in static_output that are copied from the website and NOT generated by
write_html.py

allmissions.html
time.html
energy.html
missions_tables.html


These are overview pages.

 To explore the file correction, go to the folder "processed" and double-click on "allmissions.html"
 to get a list of all possible missions. Note that some of these point to highly detailed mission
 pages (called "GOFs": Guest Observer Facilities). These links have been written to point to the
 HEASARC web server.

Examples of local pages:
ANS
ALEXIS
Lomonosov

Examples of HEASARC GOF pages:
CGRO
